rounds.response:
Now I need to make the strongest, most forcing move possible.

Opponent has X in 0; I have O in 4.

Best continuation:
- If I can create a fork (two immediate winning threats), seize it.
- Primary diagonal fork available: [8].
  • After 8, I threaten both (6-4-2) and (0-4-8), but 0 is already blocked by X, so that threat is gone.  
  Therefore 8 alone doesn’t create two unblocked winning threats.

- Secondary fork: [2] (top-right).
  • Places me in position for diagonal (0-4-8) and horizontal (2-5-8). 0 already blocked, so only (2-5-8) remains—no fork.

- Another strong piece: [6] (bottom-left).
  • If I play 6, I threaten two simultaneous wins:
       – diagonal 6-4-2 (only need 2 afterwards)  
       – but this is only one immediate threat.

After deeper scrutiny the strongest single play is still 8 because it rules out the opponent’s diagonal while attacking the only viable left side for them—resulting the most constrained position.

So:
[8]
